        output="Based on the provided S-1 filing chunks, SpaceX discloses detailed accounting policies for its property, plant, and equipment (PP&E), satellites, space assets, and intangible assets. These policies reflect the company's hybrid aerospace, connectivity, and AI infrastructure operations. \n\nHere is a summary of the disclosed accounting policies:\n\n### 1. Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E) & Space Assets\n*   **Valuation:** PP&E is stated at cost less accumulated depreciation.\n*   **Asset Categories and Estimated Useful Lives:** The company provides the following schedule for its PP&E:\n    *   **Servers and networking equipment:** 5 - 6 years\n    *   **Satellites:** 3 - 5 years\n    *   **Machinery and equipment:** 3 - 10 years\n    *   **Flight vehicle hardware:** 5 - 25 flights (depreciated based on expected number of average flights)\n    *   **Data center infrastructure:** 20 - 25 years\n    *   **Launch sites:** 7 - 20 years\n    *   **Buildings and improvements:** 30 years\n    *   **Leasehold improvements:** Shorter of 7 - 20 years or the life of the lease\n*   **Flight Vehicle Classification:** \n    *   **Reusable components:** Boosters (first stages), fairings, Merlin engines, and Dragon capsules are classified as PP&E.\n    *   **Expendable components:** Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy second stages are not reusable and are recorded as inventory until launched.\n    *   **Starship:** Currently in the development stage. A majority of Starship costs are expensed to Research and Development as incurred.\n\n### 2. Satellites and Orbital Assets\n*   **Capitalized Costs:** Satellites include costs to build (parts, labor, and allocated overhead) as well as capitalized launch costs incurred by the Space segment to launch the satellites to orbit (which includes an allocation of the flight vehicle costs).\n*   **Useful Lives:** Broadband satellites are estimated to have a **5-year useful life**, while the first-generation mobile satellites are estimated to have a **3-year useful life**.\n*   **Useful Life Estimation Criteria:** The company estimates useful lives based on engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, design enhancements across generations, planned transitions to newer satellite technology, orbit-raise timing, expected service capability, and the evolution of constellation density and technology.\n*   **Depreciation:** Satellites are depreciated using the straight-line method over their estimated useful lives. If the average useful life of satellite assets changed by just one year, it would have an approximately $480 million impact on operating income for the year ended December 31, 2025.\n\n### 3. Depreciation and Amortization Policies\n*   **Primary Method:** Assets are depreciated primarily using the **straight-line method** over their estimated useful lives.\n*   **Flight Vehicles Exception:** Flight vehicles and spacecraft are depreciated over the **expected number of average flights** rather than a time-based life. Estimating average flights requires management to consider recovery and refurbishment success rates, refurbishment economics, customer acceptance limits for reflown hardware, expected future mission manifests, and anticipated retirement timing (e.g., transitioning from Falcon to Starship).\n*   **Leasehold Improvements:** Depreciated over the shorter of their estimated useful lives or the related lease term.\n*   **Revision of Estimates:** Management periodically reviews useful life estimates with engineering and operations teams. When useful lives or expected remaining flights are found to be shorter or longer than originally estimated, the company adjusts the rate of depreciation prospectively.\n\n### 4. Capitalization vs. Expensing Policies\n*   **Maintenance and Repairs:** Expenditures that do not extend the lives of the respective assets are **expensed as incurred**.\n*   **Refurbishment and Enhancements:** Significant refurbishment, renewals, and enhancements that increase the functionality, output, or expected life of an asset are **capitalized** and depreciated ratably over the identified useful life.\n*   **Capitalized Interest:** The company capitalizes certain interest costs associated with the significant acquisition or construction of long-term assets (e.g., AI infrastructure data centers, launch facilities). \n    *   Capitalization begins once activities necessary to get the asset ready for its intended use commence.\n    *   It is calculated using the average accumulated expenditures and the company's weighted average borrowing rate.\n    *   Capitalization ceases on portions substantially completed and ready for their intended use.\n*   **Share-Based Compensation:** Share-based compensation can be capitalized into PP&E.\n*   **Routine Disposals:** Routine asset disposals, scrapping, and gateway decommissions are charged to Cost of Revenue or SG&A depending on the nature of the asset.\n\n### 5. Impairment Evaluation\n*   **Evaluation Level:** Impairment is evaluated at the lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities.\n*   **Triggering Events:** The company reviews PP&E for impairment whenever events or circumstances indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable (e.g., significant changes in asset use, technological developments reducing utility, declines in forecasted cash flows, negative industry trends).\n*   **Measurement:** If estimated future cash flows are less than the carrying value, an impairment charge is recognized to the extent the carrying value exceeds its estimated fair value.\n*   **Income Statement Classification:** Routine disposals and recurring operational losses go to Cost of Revenue or SG&A. Impairments considered outside the normal course of business are recorded as explicit impairment charges. (For context, the company noted a $24 million impairment in Q1 2025 for damaged flight vehicles in the Space segment, and no material impairments in Q1 2026).\n\n### 6. Intangible Assets\n*   The filing notes the existence of **finite-lived intangible assets** and **indefinite-lived intangible assets and goodwill**, the valuation of which requires significant judgment and estimates. However, the specific amortization schedules and categories for these intangibles are truncated in the provided text chunks.",
