        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## Closest Accounting Precedents for Future Orbital AI Compute Satellites\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) describes "orbital AI compute satellites," "orbital data centers," and "modular orbital AI compute shells" as **forward-looking plans** — with deployment targeted "as early as 2028" and ambitions to scale to "100 gigawatts of AI compute capacity on solar-powered satellites each year." Because these assets do not yet exist, the filing does not contain a dedicated accounting policy for them. However, three disclosed asset categories and policies provide the closest precedents:\n\n### 1. Existing Satellites (Starlink broadband and mobile) — closest operational precedent\n- **Classification:** Property, plant, and equipment (PP&E), stated at cost less accumulated depreciation.\n- **Capitalized costs:** Build costs (parts, labor, allocated overhead) **plus capitalized launch costs** (including an allocation of flight vehicle costs) incurred by the Space segment to place satellites in orbit.\n- **Useful lives:** 5 years for broadband satellites; 3 years for first-generation mobile satellites.\n- **Depreciation method:** Straight-line over estimated useful lives.\n- **Useful-life estimation criteria:** Engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, design enhancements across generations, planned transitions to newer technology, orbit-raise timing, expected service capability, and evolution of constellation density/technology.\n- **Sensitivity:** A one-year change in average satellite useful life would have moved 2025 operating income by approximately $480 million.\n\n### 2. AI Infrastructure / Data Centers — closest terrestrial AI precedent\n- **Classification:** PP&E (servers, networking equipment, data center infrastructure).\n- **Useful lives:** Servers and networking equipment 5–6 years; data center infrastructure 20–25 years.\n- **Capitalized interest:** Interest is capitalized during construction for significant long-term projects such as AI infrastructure data centers ($169 million capitalized in 2025).\n- **Construction in Progress (CIP):** CIP "is primarily comprised of ongoing construction and expansion of the facilities and equipment as well as AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service."\n- **CapEx scale:** AI capital expenditures reached $12,727 million in 2025 (up from $5,633 million in 2024 and $463 million in 2023).\n\n### 3. Starship (in-development flight vehicle) — closest "asset-in-development" precedent\n- **Current treatment:** Because Starship is in the development stage, the **majority of costs are expensed to Research and Development as incurred** (test flight hardware, Raptor engines, compensation, tooling, depreciation of R&D equipment, allocated overhead).\n- **Post-commercialization treatment:** Once Starship reaches commercialization (defined as delivering payload to orbit), costs generally **will be capitalized** rather than expensed as R&D, and depreciated into the cost of revenue of the segment associated with the payload delivered.\n- **Reusable vs. expendable distinction:** Reusable components (boosters, fairings, Merlin engines, Dragon capsules) are PP&E; expendable Falcon 9/Falcon Heavy second stages are inventory until launched.\n\n### Supporting capitalization vs. expensing framework\n- **Maintenance and repairs:** Expensed as incurred.\n- **Refurbishment/enhancements that extend life or functionality:** Capitalized and depreciated ratably.\n- **Impairment:** Evaluated at the lowest level with largely independent cash flows; triggering events include technological developments reducing utility, declines in forecasted cash flows, and negative industry trends.\n\n---\n\n## Does the Filing Explicitly Resolve Capitalize vs. Expense for Orbital AI Compute Satellites?\n\n**No.** The filing does **not** explicitly state whether future orbital AI compute satellites would be capitalized or expensed. The orbital AI compute satellite program is described entirely in forward-looking language (deployment "as early as 2028," scaling to "100 gigawatts" annually, "potentially millions of satellites"), and no accounting policy is provided for assets that do not yet exist.\n\n### Reasonable filing-supported inference\nAlthough not explicitly resolved, the disclosed policies strongly imply a bifurcated treatment by analogy:\n\n| Phase | Closest precedent | Implied treatment |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Pre-deployment / development** (design, prototyping, test flights) | Starship development-stage policy | Expense to R&D as incurred |\n| **Construction / pre-service** (built but not yet placed in service) | CIP for AI infrastructure | Capitalize as CIP; capitalize related interest |\n| **Operational / on-orbit** (deployed and generating service) | Existing satellite policy + AI infrastructure policy | Capitalize as PP&E (including build costs and capitalized launch costs); depreciate straight-line over estimated useful life |\n\nThe most likely useful-life analog would be the existing satellite range (3–5 years), though the filing\'s emphasis on "long-duration operation in space" for next-generation AI compute satellites could support a longer life — a determination that, per the disclosed policy, would depend on engineering studies, on-orbit performance, propellant life, and planned technology transitions. Given the disclosed sensitivity ($480 million operating-income impact per one-year change in average satellite useful life), this estimate would be highly material.\n\n### Disclosure discipline note\nThe orbital AI compute satellite program is a **roadmap target / commercialization expectation**, not a historical outcome. Any accounting treatment for these assets is therefore an inference from existing policies, not an explicit disclosure. The filing does not specify:\n- A useful life for AI compute satellites\n- Whether AI compute payloads would be depreciated separately from the satellite bus\n- Whether inter-segment launch costs would be capitalized into the satellites (as is done for Starlink today)\n- Whether any portion of compute-related R&D would continue to be expensed post-deployment\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe closest disclosed precedents are (1) the existing satellite accounting policy (capitalized as PP&E, depreciated straight-line over 3–5 years, including capitalized launch costs), (2) the AI infrastructure / data center policy (capitalized as PP&E with capitalized interest during construction), and (3) the Starship in-development policy (expensed to R&D until commercialization, then capitalized). The filing **does not explicitly resolve** whether future orbital AI compute satellites would be capitalized or expensed; by inference from these precedents, development-stage costs would likely be expensed to R&D and post-deployment operational assets would likely be capitalized as PP&E — but this is a reasonable inference, not an explicit disclosure.\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Property, Plant and Equipment policy; Satellite useful-life disclosure; Starship development-stage R&D policy; Construction in Progress and capitalized interest disclosure; AI infrastructure capital expenditure disclosure; Impairment policy"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
